I. Prediction

It must mean that it somehow came to pass,
That Bonhoefferian warning I had made:
A girl is coming, and she comes at last
Not as a notion, but a breaking blade.
I called it explosion long before,
But had no notion what such force could do,
How it could open some interior door
And yet make agony the passage through.
For what is an explosion, in the end,
But spirit driven past the point of form?
Like when in “Chopped in Half” the measures rend
The body into music, grief, and storm.
So proof exists: you came with art and flame.
The blast was real. I only missed its name.

II. The Block

You came at me with energy and art.
It was so beautiful it overran
The little fences of the thinking heart
And made a ruin of the inward man.
Yet somehow then the door was slammed as well.
I failed some hidden parenthetical sign,
Some inner gesture I could never tell,
Some law of yours that never could be mine.
You had your gears in gears, your plans in plans,
A depth of motion working out of sight;
And still I know, whatever else befell,
You offered something like cosmic bliss that night.
Then morning came. My mind rebooted clean.
The hour was blocked, as if it had not been.

III. Equal Force

And that is what still makes the whole thing strange:
After the risk you took, the force you gave,
I never wrote or called. No afterchange
Occurred. Your name went down without a wave.
From where you stood, perhaps four years went by
Inside that silence I could not explain.
The middle vanished. Then when next passed by,
You drew back with an equal force again.
That is the part that still defeats my art:
How do you make withdrawal match the throw?
Who measures out such quantities of heart,
Then takes them back so perfectly, so slow?
I call them your mysterious powers still.
Or else the odds aligned by some dark will.
